If you don’t want any rounding at all, just drop the format specifiers and let Python print the raw values. For example:

python
print("Check cohort accounting:")

print(f"Population at t+1:   {pop_t1}")
print(f"t + births - deaths: {pop_t + total_births - total_deaths}")

# Difference (should be ~0 if all is consistent except floating point noise)
print(f"Difference: {pop_t1 - (pop_t + total_births - total_deaths)}")

This will show you the full raw float or integer values (whatever the variables hold), without rounding or truncation.

Wouldnt calculating death from float result in more discrepancies? shifted is already rounded to integer
ChatGPT said:

Excellent catch 🙌 — you’re right to notice that subtlety.

Let’s walk it through carefully:

Where rounding happens

  • shifted = pop_series.shift(1, fill_value=0)
    → pop_series is already integer (since your input population by age is whole counts).
    → So shifted is integer too.

  • If you then compute survivors as float:

    python
    survived = shifted * surv_rates

    survivors are fractional.
    If you use this fractional value to compute deaths = shifted - survived, you get fractional deaths.

  • Later, you round survivors (pred = pred_float.round(0)) but keep deaths fractional.
    That’s where the mismatch shows up: rounded survivors + fractional deaths ≠ integer cohort.

The accounting triangle

For every cohort, you want:

ini
shifted = survivors + deaths

But this only holds exactly if you round both survivors and deaths in a consistent way.
If one side is rounded and the other is float, the triangle won’t close.

Options you have

  1. Round survivors first, then derive deaths from integers

    • survivors = round(shifted * survival_rate)

    • deaths = shifted - survivors
      ✅ Ensures exact accounting.
      ❌ Loses fractional precision early (small distortions accumulate across ages/years).

  2. Keep survivors as float, compute float deaths, round both at the very end

    • survivors = shifted * survival_rate

    • deaths = shifted - survivors

    • At reporting/output: round survivors and deaths consistently.
      ✅ Preserves demographic math fidelity.
      ❌ Survivors + deaths may differ by ±1 when you force integers.

  3. Hybrid approach (recommended in demography)

    • Carry floats internally.

    • At reporting/export, apply cohort reconciliation:
      adjust deaths so that

      nginx
      rounded_survivors + rounded_deaths = shifted

    This way, you preserve math balance and still output integers.

My verdict

If your priority is strict accounting (no discrepancy between t, t+1, births, deaths):
👉 Option 1 or Option 3.

If your priority is demographic accuracy over multiple years (minimizing bias from rounding):
👉 Option 2 or Option 3.

⚖️ So it boils down to what you care about more:

  • Perfect balance per year (option 1/3).

  • Higher fidelity to underlying rates across many years (option 2/3).

Do you want me to implement Option 3 (hybrid) for you — i.e. keep everything as floats internally, then at export stage reconcile survivors and deaths so every cohort balances perfectly in integers? That would give you the “best of both worlds.”

You said:
Noooo should shifted be before the survival rates are applied?
ChatGPT said:

Good catch — this is one of those subtle points in cohort-component accounting.

Here’s the principle:

  • Survival rates are probabilities applied to the entire cohort. They’re not defined on already-rounded integer counts.

  • If you round first (shifted = round(pop)), then apply survival, you’re introducing artificial error because you’re shrinking or enlarging the cohort before mortality is applied.

  • Correct order is:

  1. Take the float population in age group i at time t.

  2. Apply the survival rate → gives float survivors.

  3. Shift those survivors into age group i+1.

  4. Only at reporting/output stage do you round to integers.

So:

✅ Shift after applying survival rates (keep floats until the very end).
❌ Do not round before applying survival, or you’ll accumulate bigger discrepancies each year.

That’s why your earlier mismatch (−93) was tiny — survival + births + deaths are consistent when left as floats. If you round “shifted” too early, the differences will snowball.

Do you want me to show you a small example with numbers so you can see how rounding before vs. after survival rates changes the accounting?

In Python (or NumPy/pandas), NaN represents “Not a Number.” Any arithmetic operation involving NaN propagates it:

python
import math
import numpy as np

10 - float('nan')       # → nan
10 - np.nan              # → nan

So the result is NaN.

✅ Key point: NaN is contagious — adding, subtracting, multiplying, or dividing it by a number always results in NaN.

forecast_migrate_df["num"].sum() + forecast_migrate_df["net_m"].sum()

…you’re adding a non-existent or differently shaped column. Even if num existed, net_m is already the total (scalar), so summing it again doesn’t match row-wise sums of adj_num.

✅ To make sum(num) + sum(net_m) == sum(adj_num), you must compute net_m row-wise, not as a total scalar. Example:

python
forecast_migrate_df = pre_migrate_pop_df[["unique_id","sex","age","num"]].merge(
    migrated_pop_df[["unique_id","sex","age","adj_num"]],
    how="left",
    on=["unique_id","sex","age"]
)

forecast_migrate_df["adj_num"] = forecast_migrate_df["adj_num"].fillna(0)
forecast_migrate_df["net_m"] = forecast_migrate_df["adj_num"] - forecast_migrate_df["num"]

# Now this will always hold:
forecast_migrate_df["num"].sum() + forecast_migrate_df["net_m"].sum() == forecast_migrate_df["adj_num"].sum()

💡 Key point: net_m must be per row, not pre-aggregated, to preserve this relationship.
